1
00:00:03,770 --> 00:00:05,839
What can comfort us more

2
00:00:05,905 --> 00:00:09,042
than a bowl of warm broth

3
00:00:10,677 --> 00:00:12,879
after another long day?

4
00:00:15,248 --> 00:00:17,884
The moment we take a sip,

5
00:00:17,951 --> 00:00:20,053
the furrows in your brow disappear.

6
00:00:20,120 --> 00:00:20,954
Your forehead relaxes

7
00:00:21,021 --> 00:00:22,622
and your lips curl into a smile.

8
00:00:24,124 --> 00:00:26,393
Many Koreans say,

9
00:00:26,459 --> 00:00:27,961
"I can't have a meal without broth."

10
00:00:28,762 --> 00:00:29,963
A typical Korean meal

11
00:00:30,030 --> 00:00:31,965
centers on the bowl of broth.

12
00:00:34,367 --> 00:00:37,170
For us, it's more than
just a bowl of broth.

13
00:00:37,771 --> 00:00:39,973
It gives us comfort and strength.

14
00:00:41,241 --> 00:00:42,942
It's a way of life.

15
00:00:56,923 --> 00:01:01,494
In the past, soups were more of a means
to make a meal tastier.

16
00:01:01,561 --> 00:01:02,996
HAM YON-JI, ACTRESS

17
00:01:03,063 --> 00:01:05,598
But there's a greater variety of broth,

18
00:01:05,665 --> 00:01:07,934
and each type has become more distinct.

19
00:01:08,001 --> 00:01:11,071
I think the era of independence
for broths has come.

20
00:01:21,648 --> 00:01:22,482
GAPYEONG

21
00:01:22,549 --> 00:01:25,085
-Wow, it's so cold.
-It's been a while since I saw snow.

22
00:01:25,151 --> 00:01:26,319
-Yes.
-Yes.

23
00:01:26,386 --> 00:01:28,288
The snow looks so pretty.

24
00:01:28,354 --> 00:01:30,290
I love the sound of stepping on snow.

25
00:01:30,356 --> 00:01:32,525
I think if we eat dakbokkeumtang
when it's snowing,

26
00:01:32,592 --> 00:01:33,760
it will taste even better.

27
00:01:33,827 --> 00:01:34,694
It would be delicious.

28
00:01:34,761 --> 00:01:37,130
The location is amazing to start with.

29
00:01:37,197 --> 00:01:40,500
FOOD TASTES BETTER
ON A COLD, SNOWY DAY

30
00:01:40,567 --> 00:01:43,937
People may think that
dakbokkeumtang is a modern dish,

31
00:01:44,003 --> 00:01:45,605
but in a cookbook from 1924,

32
00:01:46,239 --> 00:01:48,475
The Greatest Modern
Joseon Recipe Book says

33
00:01:48,541 --> 00:01:51,277
that it was a famous local dish
from Kaesong.

34
00:01:51,344 --> 00:01:54,681
In those days,
instead of adding chili powder,

35
00:01:54,747 --> 00:01:57,417
they probably made the dish
using a clear broth.

36
00:01:57,484 --> 00:01:59,486
That's why dakdoritang
was also called doritang.

37
00:01:59,552 --> 00:02:03,490
There was a separate category
called doritang.

38
00:02:09,028 --> 00:02:10,630
Wow, that must be glory-bower I smell.

39
00:02:11,331 --> 00:02:13,600
-Wow, it's so cool here.
-Wow, it's…

40
00:02:14,167 --> 00:02:16,703
It feels like we stepped
into another world.

41
00:02:16,769 --> 00:02:19,139
Wow, the walls are decorated so nicely.

42
00:02:19,205 --> 00:02:21,007
It's really beautiful.

43
00:02:21,074 --> 00:02:21,908
It's so gorgeous.

44
00:02:21,975 --> 00:02:23,676
-The smoke…
-It's like an art gallery.

45
00:02:23,743 --> 00:02:25,245
-Yes.
-It feels like a gallery.

46
00:02:25,311 --> 00:02:26,446
PINEWOOD LOGS

47
00:02:30,316 --> 00:02:33,019
A PICTURESQUE VIEW
OF LOGS AND CAULDRONS

48
00:02:33,086 --> 00:02:34,654
Feels nice in front of the fire.

49
00:02:34,721 --> 00:02:36,556
-It's romantic.
-It is.

50
00:02:36,623 --> 00:02:38,124
It feels like we're going camping.

51
00:02:38,191 --> 00:02:40,860
I've never been to a restaurant
like this before.

52
00:02:40,927 --> 00:02:43,863
You haven't been to a lot of places, huh?

53
00:02:43,930 --> 00:02:47,033
I've never been to a place
without tables like this.

54
00:02:47,100 --> 00:02:49,135
This place was very popular
10 years ago, too.

55
00:02:49,202 --> 00:02:51,437
-Was it like this 10 years ago too?
-Yes, it was.

56
00:02:51,504 --> 00:02:53,940
I think they've been here for 30 years.
Sir, how old is this restaurant?

57
00:02:54,007 --> 00:02:56,943
-It's 32 years old.
-Right, 32 years.

58
00:02:57,010 --> 00:02:59,012
Was it like this from the beginning?

59
00:02:59,078 --> 00:02:59,913
Of course.

60
00:02:59,979 --> 00:03:01,414
We started out in the boonies.

61
00:03:01,481 --> 00:03:04,017
It used to be located at the top
of the mountain on an unpaved road.

62
00:03:04,083 --> 00:03:06,019
I remember that.
So you came back then, too.

63
00:03:06,085 --> 00:03:07,854
I remember now.

64
00:03:07,921 --> 00:03:09,522
You'd drive on an unpaved road,

65
00:03:09,589 --> 00:03:12,225
and then go up the mountain
for over 10 minutes.

66
00:03:12,292 --> 00:03:14,627
Then, there was a stream in front
of the place.

67
00:03:15,128 --> 00:03:16,529
People still went there.

68
00:03:19,132 --> 00:03:21,467
-Are you Min Gi-nam, the owner?
-No, my wife is the owner.

69
00:03:21,534 --> 00:03:23,870
I just tend to the fire
and get free food in exchange.

70
00:03:24,637 --> 00:03:26,940
So your wife is the owner, Min Gi-nam.

71
00:03:27,006 --> 00:03:28,007
THE REAL OWNER

72
00:03:30,210 --> 00:03:32,078
Wow!

73
00:03:32,645 --> 00:03:33,613
What a show!

74
00:03:33,680 --> 00:03:35,415
Wow!

75
00:03:35,481 --> 00:03:36,616
Wow!

76
00:03:37,317 --> 00:03:41,254
Young people these days
would love this place.

77
00:03:41,321 --> 00:03:42,789
Gotta take a picture.

78
00:03:43,456 --> 00:03:45,024
Where is my phone?

79
00:03:46,426 --> 00:03:47,260
Wait, wait.

80
00:03:48,828 --> 00:03:49,762
LOOKS GOOD

81
00:03:49,829 --> 00:03:51,130
DAKBOKKEUMTANG
BY HUH YOUNG-MAN

82
00:03:51,197 --> 00:03:52,565
When I first came here,

83
00:03:52,632 --> 00:03:55,001
they were charging over 20,000 won
10 years ago.

84
00:03:55,068 --> 00:03:57,070
It was expensive, but with huge servings.

85
00:03:57,136 --> 00:03:58,705
-There's so much chicken.
-There is.

86
00:03:58,771 --> 00:04:01,107
Is this one or two chickens?

87
00:04:01,741 --> 00:04:03,943
I don't know things like that.

88
00:04:04,010 --> 00:04:06,179
You're the best. You're awesome.

89
00:04:07,680 --> 00:04:08,915
Man in charge of the fire.

90
00:04:11,251 --> 00:04:13,853
How did you come up with this idea?

91
00:04:13,920 --> 00:04:14,988
This?

92
00:04:15,054 --> 00:04:16,623
It wasn't a new idea.

93
00:04:16,689 --> 00:04:17,624
It wasn't?

94
00:04:17,690 --> 00:04:19,692
My mom used to make buchimgae using this.

95
00:04:19,759 --> 00:04:22,428
I remembered her doing that.

96
00:04:22,495 --> 00:04:24,397
So I thought, "I should use this."

97
00:04:24,464 --> 00:04:26,032
And I tried cooking in this.

98
00:04:28,935 --> 00:04:30,703
I lived deep within the mountains.

99
00:04:30,770 --> 00:04:32,305
In the spring, I'd get herbs.

100
00:04:32,372 --> 00:04:34,407
And in the fall, I collected acorns.

101
00:04:34,474 --> 00:04:36,909
Occasionally, a stranger would pass by.

102
00:04:36,976 --> 00:04:39,646
They needed to eat,
but had no place to eat.

103
00:04:39,712 --> 00:04:41,648
They'd ask us to cook chicken.

104
00:04:41,714 --> 00:04:43,816
And so I decided,

105
00:04:43,883 --> 00:04:45,852
I'll give them something I'd eat.

106
00:04:45,918 --> 00:04:47,086
So I cooked this.

107
00:04:47,153 --> 00:04:49,022
Somehow, the word spread.

108
00:04:53,159 --> 00:04:55,261
For the seasoning, I used gochujang,

109
00:04:55,328 --> 00:04:58,464
garlic, spring onions, and chili powder.
That's how I made it.

110
00:05:00,033 --> 00:05:02,969
My mom was an only child and so am I.

111
00:05:03,036 --> 00:05:05,772
And so I have soy sauce
that's been passed down

112
00:05:05,838 --> 00:05:08,241
from my grandmother
and it's over 100 years old.

113
00:05:08,308 --> 00:05:10,843
It's over 100 years old now.
We have a special soy sauce.

114
00:05:10,910 --> 00:05:12,412
THIRD-GENERATION SOY SAUCE
RICH IN TASTE

115
00:05:14,013 --> 00:05:17,650
DAKBOKKEUMTANG

116
00:05:20,720 --> 00:05:23,156
Take a spoon and try the broth.

117
00:05:23,890 --> 00:05:27,360
START WITH HOT AND SPICY BROTH

118
00:05:28,394 --> 00:05:31,264
INSTANT NOODLES, A DELICACY
IN DAKBOKKEUMTANG

119
00:05:34,267 --> 00:05:36,169
It's a little different from dakdoritang.

120
00:05:36,235 --> 00:05:38,871
-Yeah.
-I get why it's called maeuntang.

121
00:05:38,938 --> 00:05:40,273
It's not sweet, huh?

122
00:05:40,340 --> 00:05:42,542
-Usually, it's sweet like tteokbokki.
-Yes.

123
00:05:42,608 --> 00:05:46,846
The dish is changing into something
that's either too spicy or too sweet.

124
00:05:46,913 --> 00:05:49,182
-But this isn't sweet.
-It's just spicy.

125
00:05:49,248 --> 00:05:51,084
Why is it called dakbokkeumtang?

126
00:05:51,150 --> 00:05:54,554
Bokkeum refers to a stir-fried dish
while tang refers to a stew.

127
00:05:54,620 --> 00:05:57,190
The former doesn't have broth.
The latter does.

128
00:05:57,256 --> 00:06:01,127
Usually, when broth is added to meat,
they call it a stew.

129
00:06:01,194 --> 00:06:03,529
-Not soup.
-Stew just sounds better.

130
00:06:03,596 --> 00:06:06,199
When it's called a stew,
it seems fancier, too.

131
00:06:06,265 --> 00:06:08,234
-It does.
-It seems that way.

132
00:06:09,268 --> 00:06:13,473
DAKBOKKEUMTANG HAS THE APPEAL
OF STIR-FRY AND STEW

133
00:06:14,407 --> 00:06:16,376
-Let's get more broth.
-I agree.

134
00:06:18,745 --> 00:06:22,515
Leave the extra broth here.
It's disappearing very quickly.

135
00:06:22,582 --> 00:06:24,016
What's in this stock, sir?

136
00:06:26,052 --> 00:06:27,920
I don't know anything.

137
00:06:28,855 --> 00:06:29,956
I don't know anything.

138
00:06:30,022 --> 00:06:32,191
He didn't know
how many chickens there were.

139
00:06:32,258 --> 00:06:35,495
He is very well-trained.

140
00:06:37,363 --> 00:06:41,067
"Honey, don't tell them anything.
Just tend the fire."

141
00:06:41,134 --> 00:06:42,668
I'M JUST HERE FOR THE FIRE.

142
00:06:42,735 --> 00:06:45,805
The stock is made with
whole chickens, including feet.

143
00:06:45,872 --> 00:06:49,342
The stock tastes more flavorful
because of the chicken feet.

144
00:06:49,409 --> 00:06:52,745
The collagen in chicken feet
all becomes part of the broth.

145
00:06:52,812 --> 00:06:54,180
It tastes better.

146
00:06:54,247 --> 00:06:58,217
I also add castor aralia, eleuthero,
jujube, and Mongolian milk vetch.

147
00:06:58,284 --> 00:07:01,187
I boil them in a cauldron.

148
00:07:02,855 --> 00:07:07,093
STOCK IS BOILED FOR SIX HOURS

149
00:07:08,428 --> 00:07:09,762
I guess you like chicken.

150
00:07:09,829 --> 00:07:10,930
I like chicken.

151
00:07:11,497 --> 00:07:14,600
I'm eating fast because the broth
is reducing quickly.

152
00:07:16,202 --> 00:07:20,006
HOMEGROWN CHICKEN
WITH HOT SPICES

153
00:07:26,312 --> 00:07:28,981
-The drumsticks are gone.
-Soo-young ate them all.

154
00:07:29,048 --> 00:07:30,049
I ate three.

155
00:07:30,116 --> 00:07:31,751
I shouldn't eat so much.

156
00:07:35,488 --> 00:07:37,190
The chicken is so tender, ma'am!

157
00:07:37,256 --> 00:07:38,224
It's not tough.

158
00:07:38,791 --> 00:07:40,126
Oh, my gosh, that's spicy!

159
00:07:40,193 --> 00:07:42,395
This should be called
spicy chicken maeuntang.

160
00:07:44,263 --> 00:07:47,233
-We need more stock.
-Let's make fried rice with this.

161
00:07:47,700 --> 00:07:49,135
FRIED RICE AT THE END

162
00:07:49,202 --> 00:07:51,170
I don't think I ever ate dakbokkeumtang,

163
00:07:51,237 --> 00:07:54,106
and then stir-fried rice
into the leftover broth.

164
00:07:54,173 --> 00:07:56,375
In our country,
we always add rice at the end,

165
00:07:56,442 --> 00:07:58,244
regardless of whether
it's a stew or a soup.

166
00:07:58,311 --> 00:08:01,681
FRIED RICE, DESSERT FOR KOREANS

167
00:08:03,015 --> 00:08:04,517
We're making nurungji now, right?

168
00:08:04,584 --> 00:08:06,486
After the rice goes through
a Maillard reaction,

169
00:08:06,552 --> 00:08:08,488
it is deglazed.

170
00:08:08,955 --> 00:08:10,523
And that tastes so savory.

171
00:08:17,964 --> 00:08:19,232
We're digging deep.

172
00:08:19,298 --> 00:08:20,900
DIGGING INTO THE CAULDRON

173
00:08:20,967 --> 00:08:24,203
Whenever I look at a fire,

174
00:08:24,270 --> 00:08:26,539
I always wonder what paint colors
I should use

175
00:08:26,606 --> 00:08:29,675
to recreate what I'm seeing at the moment.

176
00:08:30,243 --> 00:08:33,312
-But there's no such color.
-No, there isn't.

177
00:08:33,880 --> 00:08:35,348
That's how beautiful it is.

178
00:08:35,414 --> 00:08:38,251
I think this flame could be
this restaurant's biggest charm.

179
00:08:38,851 --> 00:08:41,487
It looks perfect right now.
It's beautiful.

180
00:08:41,554 --> 00:08:44,423
I can't see it from here, unfortunately.

181
00:08:44,857 --> 00:08:48,294
My legs are extremely warm,
but I'm enjoying the view.

182
00:08:49,028 --> 00:08:51,764
#IrresistibleMoment
#BeautifulFire

183
00:08:51,831 --> 00:08:56,068
The thing I crave the most
on a cold winter day

184
00:08:56,502 --> 00:08:58,304
is a bowl of spicy stew.

185
00:08:58,371 --> 00:09:01,874
You can gather
three or four of your good friends

186
00:09:01,941 --> 00:09:03,276
and satiate your hunger.

187
00:09:03,943 --> 00:09:06,546
A dish you can enjoy with your friends is

188
00:09:06,946 --> 00:09:08,414
dakbokkeumtang.

189
00:09:08,481 --> 00:09:09,849
THE JOY OF SHARING FOOD
WITH FRIENDS

190
00:09:12,184 --> 00:09:15,221
UIJEONGBU

191
00:09:16,289 --> 00:09:18,724
This wasn't here before.

192
00:09:18,791 --> 00:09:20,359
But there is a budae jjigae street now.

193
00:09:20,426 --> 00:09:22,161
There is a street now.

194
00:09:22,228 --> 00:09:24,130
A UIJEONGBU LANDMARK
BUDAE JJIGAE STREET

195
00:09:24,196 --> 00:09:28,034
BUDAE JJIGAE STREET
IN THE HEART OF UIJEONGBU

196
00:09:28,100 --> 00:09:31,237
MORE THAN A DOZEN BUDAE JJIGAE
PLACES ON ONE STREET

197
00:09:33,172 --> 00:09:34,473
Hello.

198
00:09:34,540 --> 00:09:36,175
Hello!

199
00:09:36,242 --> 00:09:37,643
-Let's sit here.
-Where?

200
00:09:37,710 --> 00:09:38,744
Let's sit.

201
00:09:38,811 --> 00:09:42,281
Sir, when did you first come here?
Your cartoons are on the wall.

202
00:09:42,348 --> 00:09:45,651
-20 years ago.
-You came here 20 years ago?

203
00:09:45,718 --> 00:09:48,154
Back then, this was
the only restaurant here, right?

204
00:09:48,220 --> 00:09:50,389
I think there were two or three more.

205
00:09:51,591 --> 00:09:54,427
THE ORIGINAL UIJEONGBU
BUDAE JJIGAE RESTAURANT

206
00:09:54,894 --> 00:09:57,530
My grandmother was the founder.

207
00:09:57,597 --> 00:09:59,899
She opened the restaurant in 1960.

208
00:09:59,966 --> 00:10:03,069
She was a street vendor at first.

209
00:10:03,135 --> 00:10:04,904
And after that,

210
00:10:04,971 --> 00:10:08,007
Koreans working in the US Army bases

211
00:10:08,074 --> 00:10:10,142
brought her different ingredients

212
00:10:10,209 --> 00:10:12,011
like ham and sausage.

213
00:10:12,078 --> 00:10:14,113
At first, she made it a stir-fried dish

214
00:10:14,180 --> 00:10:18,484
so people could eat it
while they drank alcohol.

215
00:10:18,551 --> 00:10:24,023
But her regulars wanted
something with broth, like stews.

216
00:10:24,090 --> 00:10:27,093
So she added ham, sausage, gochujang,

217
00:10:28,761 --> 00:10:31,530
kimchi, and other ingredients.
And she boiled them in broth.

218
00:10:31,597 --> 00:10:33,733
People loved it.

219
00:10:34,300 --> 00:10:37,103
And she continued to sell the dish
known as budae jjigae.

220
00:10:37,703 --> 00:10:39,038
You just use regular water.

221
00:10:39,105 --> 00:10:40,640
This isn't water.

222
00:10:40,706 --> 00:10:43,743
And it's not beef stock.
It's a vegetable stock we made.

223
00:10:43,809 --> 00:10:45,177
Really?

224
00:10:45,244 --> 00:10:47,680
VEGETABLE STOCK, THE SECRET
TO BUDAE JJIGAE BROTH

225
00:10:47,747 --> 00:10:49,882
One of the basic ingredients is scallions.

226
00:10:49,949 --> 00:10:52,418
We also add onions and spring onion roots.

227
00:10:52,985 --> 00:10:56,322
We add an assortment of vegetables

228
00:10:56,389 --> 00:10:58,491
and we boil them for over
two and a half hours.

229
00:10:59,525 --> 00:11:01,127
So our budae jjigae is a stew

230
00:11:01,193 --> 00:11:05,097
made with vegetable stock
that tastes clean and simple.

231
00:11:05,164 --> 00:11:07,033
UIJEONGBU BUDAE JJIGAE
HAS A CLEAN, REFRESHING TASTE

232
00:11:08,100 --> 00:11:09,502
To be honest,

233
00:11:09,568 --> 00:11:12,438
it's my first time eating
Uijeongbu-style budae jjigae.

234
00:11:12,505 --> 00:11:15,041
I heard the ones from Uijeongbu
have lighter broths.

235
00:11:15,107 --> 00:11:17,410
And so you can taste the kimchi more.

236
00:11:17,476 --> 00:11:18,844
And the ones from Songtan

237
00:11:18,911 --> 00:11:22,515
add cheese, bacon, and baked beans.

238
00:11:22,581 --> 00:11:25,184
-And they add more ham too.
-They add a lot.

239
00:11:25,251 --> 00:11:28,921
So I'm used to eating budae jjigae
made with thick beef bone broth.

240
00:11:28,988 --> 00:11:30,156
SONGTAN BUDAE JJIGAE,
THICK AND DEEP FLAVOR

241
00:11:30,222 --> 00:11:32,758
I'm looking forward to tasting this.

242
00:11:35,561 --> 00:11:40,099
UIJEONGBU BUDAE JJIGAE

243
00:11:41,000 --> 00:11:42,968
A pot full of boiling-hot budae jjigae.

244
00:11:43,035 --> 00:11:45,438
With onions.

245
00:11:45,504 --> 00:11:47,506
And kimchi.

246
00:11:49,442 --> 00:11:52,078
Plus ingredients like sausage and ham.

247
00:11:52,611 --> 00:11:55,848
HAM AND SAUSAGE
YIELD THE STEW'S TASTE

